<item>
            <title>[JDK-8301564] Non-C-heap allocated ResourceHashtable keys and values must have trivial destructor</title>
                <link>https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8301564</link>
                <project id="10100" key="JDK">JDK</project>
                    <description>ResourceHashtableBase deletes the ResourceHashtableNode only when the table is allocated on the C heap. For example:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/09bfbf80639f059563fcd4432995b8c380cea298/src/hotspot/share/utilities/resourceHash.hpp#L99-L113&quot;&gt;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/09bfbf80639f059563fcd4432995b8c380cea298/src/hotspot/share/utilities/resourceHash.hpp#L99-L113&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
When &amp;quot;delete&amp;quot; is used, the destructors for ResourceHashtableNode::_key and ResourceHashtableNode::_value are also called. These destructors can perform clean up as necessary.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
We should add a static assert that if the ResourceHashtable is not C-Heap allocated, the key and value must be types that are trivially destructible (see &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/is_destructible)&quot;&gt;https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/is_destructible)&lt;/a&gt;. Otherwise, the clean up expected by the key and value types will never happen. </description>
